<br>
Most likely the following components will work just about as well in any new system as tey will in the old one as the technological advances just aren't there.<br>
<br>
Modem - Particularly if it is PCI (which stink) but that is another story.  If ISA you may have trouble finding a motherboard with more than one ISA slot, which could affect the following.<br>
<br>
Sound Card - Again, in many older PC's these were ISA.  The advances in Sound Card technology can barely be heard without a $500 set of speakers, so don't waste money upgrading this, especially since most people turn most ambient sounds off anyhow.<br>
<br>
Network Card (NIC) - In the case of broadband (Cable or DSL) you will probably have a NIC instead of a modem.  This can once again be re-used as technology here hasn't changed one iota in 10 years on the personal computer side.<br>
<br>
Keyboard &amp; Mouse - Can most likely be re-used also, just be cautious of whether or not you will have to get adapters to convert the cable to fit in PS/2 type sockets. <br>
<br>
Speakers - This one is a given.  Even if you keep the old PC around for non-gaming stuff, you can still re-use the speakers as you won't need them on a non-gaming PC, unless you like to listen to CD's.<br>
<br>
So, with all that in mind, take another list at the top.  It could very well narrow down your cost, to somethign very affordable.<br>
<br>
Also, don't hesitate to visit you local PC parts store (as in a computer hardware only store, not Best-Buy or CompUSA).  Quite frequently they will let you pick out your components and put them all together for you for a small charge.  Just tell them you want a gaming PC, and take the list from the first reply to this post with ya.  It should get you through it easily.<br>
<br>
Also, if you buy the PC and are totally lost on building it, don't be afraid to ask questions.  I have built so many I could almost do it blindfolded.  And one tip, figure out if you need the USB, Serial, or Parallel ports.  If you don't turn them off in BIOS as it will free up IRQ's from the get go for less hassle.  On that note, never install more than the vid card the first time you boot it up.  Afterwards I recommend adding one card at a time, powering down between adds.  It allows the operating system to think abotu that one card only, and helps you to know which card is causing problems right away.  If you add them all at once, it can take forever to figure out where your probelm is.<br>
<br>
<br>
Laters,<br>
Talas <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/blottdrinal.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=qillsiderodromophobia>Qill Siderodromophobia</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/24/01 8:36:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/flottdrinalfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=307.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Computer Help - once again</span><hr size=1> First off, Get HELP the hard part is getting it to work right!<br>
