<br>
One point to add though.  The last three chipsets of AMD (Athlon, Duron and Thunderbird) actually seem to outperfrom the Intel chipsets of similar speed, and there cost is much lower, but ... and a big but here, I continue to receive complaint after complaint of random lockups with the AMD chips.  A couple of them got so bad I completely swapped out the PC's, which still lock up, but the users psychological well-being is better off.  Only a few companies actually test that kind of performance, and it is hard to gauge, but it goes without saying it doesn't matter how fast it is if it locks up once per hour.<br>
<br>
Note, the above was on gaming systems.  Many PC benchmarks do not run full tests on a wide variety of games or configurations.  Generally it is &quot;this chip is this PC, running Quake (insert one or two other games here)&quot;.  This allows the vendors to know ahead of time how to set up the PC's to run best on certain benchmarks, and configure their system to actually run those one or two particular games.  Didn't you ever work in fast food where you had to scrub the entire place down the day before an inspection, which is the only day in the whole year you had to clean anything?  The managers knew the inspection was coming and if they passed that one test they in clear sailing for the rest of the year.<br>
<br>
If these PC's were to actually run the games for more than a few minutes you would start to see memory leakage and many other little isses come up that can cause lockups.  One thing about being the &quot;big boy&quot; as Intel has, is that they have ironed out register swapping to memory and other data and memory leakage problems that still plague the AMD chips.  AMD meanwhile has focused all its efforts around marketing and delivering a faster chip going by the benchmarks.  <br>
<br>
It is kind of like buying a twinked character off of Ebay vs. actually playing the character from day one, you learn how to play, which carris alot of weight.  In this scenario think of Intel as the long time player, while AMD came in asking where Burned Woods is.  Granted, AMD has been around a while, but they have a terrible history in chip-making post-486 machines.  Another ananlogy would be the Dino-DNA part of Jurassic (sp?) Park.  Silly story line, but it makes sense.  Jumping into anything at the very end will not give you the experience neccessary to do a complete and thorough job.  I can't imagine just reading the book of Revelations and then going out to try and spread Christianity throughout the world.  I just don't think I would be able to grasp the full teachings of the bible.<br>
<br>
