<br>
Retail - Same exact product as bought in store.  Usually only a small fraction cheaper, and as Chey noted above (in the sound card section), the shipping we basically equal it out.  In these cases you might as well buy local in case it is defective.  Buying locally will often give you the freedom of returning a defective product to the retailer for an exchange within a given period of time.  Whereas, buying over the Internet generally means you have to go through the manufacturer and generally end up getting a refurbished model.<br>
<br>
White Box - Same as retail, only in a generic (aka White) box.  You generally get all the same materials as retail version, but with no post sale manufacturer support.  The drivers can still be gotten from the manufacturers web site and generally work exactly the same.<br>
<br>
OEM - There are two tyes of OEM products and this is what makes it so much fun to deal with .. sarcasm there.  Unfortunately they are no differentiated in most ads.  The difference comes in who the OEM comes from.  I will use a 3Com Network Card as the example, with one OEM being direct from 3Com, and the other being through a COMPAQ parts reseller.<br>
<br>
Type 1 - 3COM OEM - This is generally the same card as you would buy off the shelf at CompUSA or whatever in the Retail box.  The manufacturers drivers can be expected to work correctly, but you will have no support.  This is very very similiar to the white box mentioned above.  The difference is that this is only supposed to be sold to someone to be built into an entire machien before the customer receives it.  It is not intended to be sold directly to customers unless they are ordering an entire PC.  Yet, do to the nature of the business and the lack of policing this business, these OEM parts are sold straight to customers all the time.  The only OEM products you shoudl be careful of are the Microsoft ones, because they have been known to shut down retailers selling these stand alone and using the records to come after owners.  They haven't done this in a long time, but with the government being so stupid with the monopoly thing, you can expect Microsoft to be in a bad mood.<br>
<br>
Type 2 - Here is where you can get ripped off big time.  Say you buy a 3Com Network Card OEM from a Compaq parts reseller.  What you are most likely getting is a Network Card that has been &quot;Flashed&quot; by Compaq to work specifically with their systems.  This is done by PC manufacturers (Compaq) in order to get cut rate deals from the producers (3Com) who know that their low-priced OEM cards are not being resold for profit only.  What this does is cause your Plug and Play system to read it as a Compaq such and such Network Card rather than a 3Com card, and also will prevent it from being able to use 3Com's drivers.  Instead you have to use a Compaq driver for the card, which is essentially the same but with a the driver is Compaq Id'ed in it's information header, thus the Flash ROM chip on the card will recognize it.  <br>
<br>
Note that this last OEM example has become a huge player in the 3D video card market.  Diamond was a huge proponent of this and on some of the Diamond Cards with the Nvidia chipset, you could not get the manufacturers drivers to work correctly.  This meant you had to get Diamonds drivers, which would generall y be 4-6 months behind the manufacturers drivers, thus making it impossible to stay up to date.  Fortunately, Diamond saw the stupidity in this and now allows you to download Firmware (Flash ROM) updates to remove this liability.  Most of the newer GeForce cards have learned from this and will allow you to download the latest drivers from Nvidia or use the Video Card Manufacturers driver.  <br>
<br>
To sum up.  Always be careful when buying any component other than retail versions, especially when a driver will need to be loaded.  It is the worst feeling ever to save $20 on a $100 item only to find you have to search the internet for hours to download the right driver to make it work.  In other words, a little more money now, a lot less headache later.  Of course, this isn't as bad as it used to be, since many folks can download these drivers in minutes using broadband, but it used to take hours sometimes using dial-up modems.  Ick.<br>
